[src:css-houdini/api-worklet] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:css-houdini/api-worklet] It’s been available across browsers since April 2021.
[src:css-houdini/api-worklet] The **`Worklet`** interface is a lightweight version of Web Workers and gives developers access to low-level parts of the rendering pipeline.
[src:css-houdini/api-worklet] With Worklets, you can run JavaScript and WebAssembly code to do graphics rendering or audio processing where high performance is required.
[src:css-houdini/api-worklet] Worklets allow static import of ECMAScript modules, if supported, using `import`.
[src:css-houdini/api-worklet] Dynamic import is disallowed by the specification — calling `import()` will throw.
[src:css-houdini/api-worklet] Worklets are restricted to specific use cases; they cannot be used for arbitrary computations like Web Workers.
[src:css-houdini/api-worklet] The `Worklet` interface abstracts properties and methods common to all kind of worklets, and cannot be created directly.
[src:css-houdini/api-worklet] For 3D rendering with WebGL, you don't use worklets.
[src:css-houdini/api-worklet] Instead, you write vertex shaders and fragment shaders using GLSL code, and those shaders will then run on the graphics card.
[src:css-houdini/api-worklet] Adds the script module at the given URL to the current worklet.
[src:css-houdini/css-painting-api] This feature is not Baseline because it does not work in some of the most widely-used browsers.
[src:css-houdini/css-painting-api] The CSS Painting API — part of the CSS Houdini umbrella of APIs — allows developers to write JavaScript functions that can draw directly into an element's background, border, or content.
[src:css-houdini/css-painting-api] Essentially, the CSS Painting API contains functionality allowing developers to create custom values for `paint()`, a CSS `<image>` function.
[src:css-houdini/css-painting-api] You can then apply these values to properties like `background-image` to set complex custom backgrounds on an element.
[src:css-houdini/css-painting-api] The API defines a `worklet` that can be used to programmatically generate an image that responds to computed style changes.
[src:css-houdini/css-painting-api] To find out more about how this is used, consult Using the CSS Painting API.
[src:css-houdini/css-painting-api] The global execution context of the paint worklet.
[src:css-houdini/css-painting-api] The rendering context for the CSS Painting API's rendering context for drawing to the bitmap.
[src:css-houdini/css-painting-api] Represents the size of the output bitmap that the author should draw.
[src:css-houdini/css-painting-api] The following example creates a list of items with a background image that rotates between three different colors and three widths.
[src:css-houdini/css-painting-api] In a supporting browser you will see something like the image below.
[src:css-houdini/css-painting-api] To achieve this we'll define two custom CSS properties, `--box-color` and `--width-subtractor`.
[src:css-houdini/css-painting-api] The worklet is an external JavaScript file (in this case we've called it `boxbg.js`) which defines a paint `worklet`.
[src:css-houdini/css-painting-api] We used the `inputProperties()` method in the `registerPaint()` class to get the values of two custom properties set on an element that has `boxbg` applied to it and then used those within our `paint()` function.
[src:css-houdini/css-painting-api] The `inputProperties()` method can return all properties affecting the element, not just custom properties.
[src:css-houdini/css-painting-api] In our CSS, we define the `--box-color` and `--width-subtractor` custom properties.
[src:css-houdini/css-painting-api] The setup and logic of the paint worklet is in the external script.
[src:css-houdini/css-painting-api] While you can't play with the worklet's script, you can alter the custom property values in DevTools to change the colors and width of the background image.
[src:css-houdini/css-properties-and-values-api] Since July 2024, this feature works across the latest devices and browser versions.
[src:css-houdini/css-properties-and-values-api] This feature might not work in older devices or browsers.
[src:css-houdini/css-properties-and-values-api] The **CSS Properties and Values API** — part of the CSS Houdini umbrella of APIs — allows developers to explicitly define their CSS custom properties, allowing for property type checking, default values, and properties that do or do not inherit their value.
[src:css-houdini/css-properties-and-values-api] Defines how a browser should parse CSS custom properties.
[src:css-houdini/css-properties-and-values-api] Access this interface through `CSS.registerProperty` in JavaScript.
[src:css-houdini/css-properties-and-values-api] Access this interface through `@property` at-rule in CSS.
[src:css-houdini/css-properties-and-values-api] The following will register a custom property named `--my-color` using `CSS.registerProperty` in JavaScript.
[src:css-houdini/css-property] The **`@property`** CSS at-rule is used to explicitly define CSS custom properties, allowing for property type checking and constraining, setting default values, and defining whether a custom property can inherit values or not.
[src:css-houdini/css-property] The custom property name is a `<dashed-ident>` that starts with `--` and is followed by a valid, user-defined identifier.
[src:css-houdini/css-property] A string that describes the allowed value types for the registered custom property.
[src:css-houdini/css-property] A boolean value that controls whether the custom property registration specified by `@property` inherits by default.
[src:css-houdini/css-property] A value that sets the starting value for the property.
[src:css-houdini/css-property] The `@property` at-rule is part of the CSS Houdini set of APIs.
[src:css-houdini/css-property] It allows developers to explicitly define CSS custom properties, allowing for property type checking and constraining, setting default values, and defining whether a custom property can inherit values or not.
[src:css-houdini/css-property] The `@property` rule enables custom property registration directly inside stylesheets without requiring any JavaScript.
[src:css-houdini/css-property] Valid `@property` rules produce registered custom properties, producing the same effect as calling `registerProperty()` with equivalent parameters.
[src:css-houdini/css-property] If multiple valid `@property` rules are defined using the same name, the last one in stylesheet order "wins".
[src:css-houdini/css-property] If custom properties are registered with the same name using `@property` in CSS and `CSS.registerProperty()` in JavaScript, the JavaScript registration wins.
[src:css-houdini/css-property] In this example, we use the `@property` at-rule to declare two custom properties, and then use those properties in our style declarations.
[src:css-houdini/css-property] The paragraph should be `200px` wide, with a purple background and white text.
[src:css-houdini/css-property] In this example, we define a custom property called `--progress` using `@property`: this accepts `<percentage>` values and has an initial value of `25%`.
[src:css-houdini/css-property] We use `--progress` to define the position value of the color stops in a `linear-gradient()`, specifying where a green color stops, and black starts.
[src:css-houdini/css-property] We then animate the value of `--progress` to `100%` over 2.5 seconds, giving the effect of animating a progress bar.
[src:css-houdini/houdini-apis] Houdini is a set of low-level APIs that exposes parts of the CSS engine, giving developers the power to extend CSS by hooking into the styling and layout process of a browser's rendering engine.
[src:css-houdini/houdini-apis] Houdini is a group of APIs that give developers direct access to the CSS Object Model (CSSOM), enabling developers to write code the browser can parse as CSS, thereby creating new CSS features without waiting for them to be implemented natively in browsers.
[src:css-houdini/houdini-apis] Houdini enables faster parse times than using JavaScript `HTMLElement.style` for style changes.
[src:css-houdini/houdini-apis] Browsers parse the CSSOM — including layout, paint, and composite processes — before applying any style updates found in scripts.
[src:css-houdini/houdini-apis] In addition, layout, paint, and composite processes are repeated for JavaScript style updates.
[src:css-houdini/houdini-apis] Houdini code doesn't wait for that first rendering cycle to be complete.
[src:css-houdini/houdini-apis] Rather, it is included in that first cycle — creating renderable, understandable styles.
[src:css-houdini/houdini-apis] Houdini provides an object-based API for working with CSS values in JavaScript.
[src:css-houdini/houdini-apis] Houdini's CSS Typed Object Model API is a CSS Object Model with types and methods, exposing values as JavaScript objects making for more intuitive CSS manipulation than previous string based `HTMLElement.style` manipulations.
[src:css-houdini/houdini-apis] Every element and style sheet rule has a style map which is accessible via its `StylePropertyMap`.
[src:css-houdini/houdini-apis] A feature of CSS Houdini is the `Worklet`.
[src:css-houdini/houdini-apis] With worklets, you can create modular CSS, requiring a single line of JavaScript to import configurable components: no pre-processors, post-processors or JavaScript frameworks needed.
[src:css-houdini/houdini-apis] This added module contains `PaintWorkletGlobalScope.registerPaint` functions, which register completely configurable worklets.
[src:css-houdini/houdini-apis] The CSS `paint()` function is an additional function supported by the `<image>` type.
[src:css-houdini/houdini-apis] It takes parameters that include the name of the worklet, plus additional parameters needed by the worklet.
[src:css-houdini/houdini-apis] The worklet also has access to the element's custom properties: they don't need to be passed as function arguments.
[src:css-houdini/houdini-apis] In the following example the `paint()` function is passed a worklet called `my-component`.
[src:css-houdini/houdini-apis] Below you can find links to the main reference pages covering the APIs that fall under the Houdini umbrella, along with links to guides to help you if you need guidance in learning how to use them.
[src:css-houdini/houdini-apis] Defines an API for registering new CSS properties.
[src:css-houdini/houdini-apis] Properties registered using this API are provided with a parse syntax that defines a type, inheritance behavior, and an initial value.
[src:css-houdini/houdini-apis] Converting CSSOM value strings into meaningfully typed JavaScript representations and back can incur a significant performance overhead.
[src:css-houdini/houdini-apis] The CSS Typed OM exposes CSS values as typed JavaScript objects to allow their performant manipulation.
[src:css-houdini/houdini-apis] Developed to improve the extensibility of CSS, the Painting API allows developers to write JavaScript functions that can draw directly into an element's background, border, or content via the `paint()` CSS function.
[src:css-houdini/houdini-apis] An API for running scripts in various stages of the rendering pipeline independent of the main JavaScript execution environment.
[src:css-houdini/houdini-apis] Worklets are conceptually similar to Web Workers, and are called by and extend the rendering engine.
[src:css-houdini/houdini-apis] Designed to improve the extensibility of CSS, this API enables developers to write their own layout algorithms, like masonry or line snapping.
[src:css-houdini/houdini-apis] An API exposing the CSS parser more directly, for parsing arbitrary CSS-like languages into a mildly typed representation.
[src:css-houdini/houdini-apis] An API exposing font metrics, giving access to typographic layout results.
[src:css-houdini/registerproperty-static] The **`CSS.registerProperty()`** static method registers custom properties, allowing for property type checking, default values, and properties that do or do not inherit their value.
[src:css-houdini/registerproperty-static] Registering a custom property allows you to tell the browser how the custom property should behave; what types are allowed, whether the custom property inherits its value, and what the default value of the custom property is.
[src:css-houdini/registerproperty-static] A string representing the `<dashed-ident>` name of the property being defined.
[src:css-houdini/registerproperty-static] A string representing the expected syntax of the defined property.
[src:css-houdini/registerproperty-static] A boolean value defining whether the defined property should be inherited (`true`), or not (`false`).
[src:css-houdini/registerproperty-static] A string representing the initial value of the defined property.
[src:css-houdini/registerproperty-static] The given `name` has already been registered.
[src:css-houdini/registerproperty-static] The given `name` isn't a valid custom property name (starts with two dashes, e.g., `--foo`).
[src:css-houdini/registerproperty-static] The required `name` and/or `inherits` dictionary members were not provided.
[src:css-houdini/registerproperty-static] In this example, the custom property `--my-color` has been registered using the syntax `<color>`.
[src:css-houdini/registerproperty-static] We can now use that property to transition a gradient on hover or focus.
[src:css-houdini/registerproperty-static] Notice that with the registered property, the transition works, but it doesn't work with the unregistered property!
